	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96654247123910><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=96654247123910>Death by Kiting =)</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=96654247123910#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=371><span id=Scholar>MandicusLifescourge</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>355 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Aug 17th 4:01 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Here is a little info about pet kiting.&nbsp;&nbsp;Some say that it is cowardiss, I say that they are misinformed.<br><br>Step 1 - Summon pet<br><br>Step 2 - Test your pet out on a low mob.  IE low blue or green.  If it is hitting for close to the max damage (within 2 damage) keep the pet.  If it is not, /pet get lost and resummon.  Repeat process until you have highest, or second highest lvl pet allowed by your summon pet spell.<br><br>Step 3 - SoW your pet and yourself.  Also if you are fighting high blue, whites, or yellows, you want to keep regen or chloro on at all times on both you and your pet.  Until your pet gets up in damage (41 or 43) it will regen VERY slow.  Up until those levels you need to keep regen on them.<br><br>Step 4 - /pet no taunt (should be obvious)<br><br>Note - If you are currently working on raising skill in a certain field like evocation or conjuration you need to adapt your whole style of pet kiting so that you are using those spells more often.  Also you need to do MORE damage than your pet does at all times; if you are not doing enough damage the mob will turn around and whoop your pet bad.  If you are not paying attention your pet will probably die and you will need to zone. (depending on how much ac gear, mana, and level of the target)<br><br>A good thing to do when mob gets pissed at your pet is just blast him with a nuke.  That will get its attention fast.<br><br>Step 5 - The pull.  This one is really been debated throughest lives of shamen.  Some feel that even though you are pet kiting you should pull with a slow spell.  I personally think that if you are fighting low blue mobs then you should pull with disease, sic pet and then do poison.  Others think that you need to pull with a resist spell.  I would say only pull with a low level resist spell.  The higher level resist spells cost WAY too much mana to be mana efficient.  You should only use the resist debuffers when fighting mid to high blues, whites, and yellows.<br><br>Facts about pet kiting:<br>At lvl 34 you CAN kill red con mobs.<br>At lvl 45 you CAN'T kill red con mobs, but you could kill lvl 40 to 43 or so mobs with great difficulty.<br>If you are pulling high blue to yellow mobs and you get another mob jumping in of the same nature, your pet is dead; let it go.<br>You CAN triple kite with a pet on low blue and green mobs and still end up with a bub of mana or so for downtime.<br>You CAN outrun any mob that does not have Spirit of Wolf cast upon them.  Including Kunark Rhinos, tigers, ice giants, hill giants.<br>You ARE wasting your time pet kiting anything with tons of hitpoints (giants); It takes about 3 to 4 bubs for a shaman to drop a high blue giant.  It only takes about 2 to 3 to drop any other high blue non-caster.<br>Last fact:<br>You can get almost every ounce of experience from level 34 to 45+ pet kiting. Its just boring =P<br><br>Leave your flames at home, you will be disappointed in my responce.<br><br>Any questions?<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Grimlach Blackhand - Prophet, Innoruuk server.</td></tr>
