	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9666190534602><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=9666190534602>RE: Depending on level</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=9666190534602#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 1:17 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.83]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I just wanted to refine the 'depends on level' concept a bet more from 1 to 27.&nbsp;&nbsp;I have played two shamans (Barb to 20, Iksar to 27).  Although i grouped frequently as the Barb, the Iksar has played predominantly solo.  <br><br>From level 1 to 8, you are a melee machine, using you spells to either soften up your opponent or to heal youself to reduce down time.<br><br>From level 9 to 18, I was still doing most of my damage in melee, but i found it necessary to use more mana....The most efficient approach was:  Speed debuff, Dot and then melee.<br><br>After level 19, I could no longer stand toe to toe with hard blues....If i tried to melee them, they ripped me to shreds.   But if i used my spells, i could still kill blues, some whites (and if necessary, a yellow).  You can do this either with nuke-kiting (mostly from 19-23rd) or root-dotting (mostly from 24th to 28th).<br><br>Kiting is well understood and explained elsewhere, but briefly...You sow your self, nuke the mob and start running....Eventually you learn how long to run before you can stop, renuke and start running before it gets to you.  Drawbacks...You tend to outrun the mob if you arent careful, esp if there are pathing problems in zone; You can easily come across a second aggro mob (I usually ran back and forth across a specific path), You can get in trouble if your sow drops.<br><br>Root-Dotting is a safer approach once you get your 24th level DOT...Long duration DOT(affliction); Root; Short duration DOT (envenomed breath)...Reroot and reDOT as necessary...Once it is nearly dead, melee to finish it off.  The real advantage of this is that while it is dying from DOT, you are medding/ regening.  And, if you find your roots just wont stick, you can still revert to kiting or just flat-out run away.<br><br><br><br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
