	   <a name=9665366378223></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9665366378223><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=9665366378223>The Making of a Shaman</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=9665366378223#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=360><span id= >Curr</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>5 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Aug 17th 2:23 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>THE MAKING OF A SHAMAN<br><br>	Listen my young ones and perhaps I can share some things I have learned in many days of travel in Norrath.&nbsp;&nbsp;I have had many good teachers along the way and remembered much from what I was told. The way is long and the dangers are great but you will prevail with a few basic tools&#8230;<br><br>	So, you have chosen to be a healer. It is an honorable position you have chosen be it Shaman or Cleric.  I shall share with you a few things for you to remember as you travel and as you group.  Most of what you hear will be aimed at the apprentice Shaman but the Cleric may also learn much.<br>	When you join a group the first thing you must do is determine what your role in the group is to be and what other classes are present.  If you are to be a buffer/melee then the spells you memorize will be different than if you are the primary healer. You also need to know who the group is assisting on in battle so as not to mess up mesmerize spells cast by enchanters and such.<br> If you, as a Shaman are chosen to be a buffer and blaster then you need to know what other blasters are present and what spells they are casting. Some DoT & AoE spells DO NOT stack.  In order to not waste mana get these things worked out ahead of time.  Know what spells you will be casting in battle and when you will be casting them. As far as buffs go you must put some thought into this. I myself find out up front who is the primary tank.  I keep them buffed.  Now you will get requests from all other party members wanting buffs also. If I am needed to blast, the group will be told that I can buff them all and re-med and cause downtime (most melee types get buffed and want to immediately go into battle) or just keep the primary tank buffed and do the others as I get EXTRA mana. If I am not needed to melee, then I buff em all as I get mana and keep written record of my buff order.  This saves all those &#8216; I need STR again&#8221; tells during battle because I know ahead of time and re-buff before they even know its going.  If possible I try to keep everyone Sow and all Melees Regened.  You can also cast a few buffs on yourself that increase you HP when you get cannibalize.  This will give you more HP to convert into mana when needed. Now, as with all casters remember, DO NOT blast the minute the mob is near. This will cause big problems I will discuss later under the healer section. Also, when you get the quickness spell ask other casters if they are casting a speed spell or if the warriors proc a haste effect, they will overwrite quick and you wasted mana again. Also, on a final note, as a buffer/melee I still save a bubble or so of mana for emergency heals. Sometimes the Cleric gets in trouble and nothing makes a healer happier than to be HEALED when they are getting mobbed.<br>	First, remember you are there to keep group members alive at all cost.  If you are the primary, You DO NOT expose yourself to danger until it is clear you will not be attacked or you are OOM and the tanks are in trouble, then help as much as you can. Sometimes helping is sitting and medding during battle for mana for a heal that will save a tanks life.  Most tanks will die for the healer but it makes them a little mad to see you with full health when they re-appear after dying. There is no glory in gating with full health and allowing the tanks to die.  There is also no glory in getting killed through your own stupidity, or causing your tank problems by pulling MoBs from him onto yourself.  Tanks are too busy bashin & slamin & kickin to be constantly taunting stuff of a shammie who thought he would take a few swings at a HG that he Doted and the Giant hasn&#8217;t forgotten it!  Now as a healer I do not heal the tanks until they are at least under 3 bubbles. If the puller is dropping health quickly then I will heal him as soon as he is in range, but be ready for the mob to come to you.  If the tanks are doing their job they will be pulling him off you ASAP. Do not scurry about and make this hard for them to do.  Stand and take a few hits first to allow them to do some damage then back slowly away.  Tanks have an obligation to be constantly watching the healers and casters to keep Mob&#8217;s off them. Sometimes I do a group tell stating &#8220;ON ME&#8221; in case they forgot to watch hehe.  But again I wait to heal until the MOB is good and mad at the tank.  Also a bubble of new health every few seconds is better than a 3 bubble heal at one time and aggroing the MOB on you.  As primary I keep myself buffed ONLY with the buffs that increase Hp&#8217;s. I do not keep myself fully buffed and allow my tanks to go un-healed because I thought I needed to be ready to gate.  I despise seeing a Shaman at full health, also after a battle and all his warriors at 2 bubbles of health.  If the Shaman is doing his job as healer correctly he will be cannibalizing during battle and healing for all he is worth.  I do not sacrifice my tanks to save myself.  I have cannibalized to as low as ½ bubble during battle and cast the heal that saved us all.  If not dying is that important to you then don&#8217;t group and fight where you may die.  It is also important that you keep the entire group aware of your mana level. I sometimes fudge this if needed to the low side so as to slow down the over zealous puller.<br><br>A WORD FOR NON TANK TYPES<br>There is nothing a healer hates more than having to heal a Wizard or Mage other non melee type 3 times to keep him alive during battle and use up mana meant for the tanks. Mana spent on the non-melee type is mana not spent wisely.  As a semi tank do not rob the warriors of their mana by getting in trouble.<br><br><br>A CLOSING THOUGHT<br>	I will leave you with this. I have left many groups after 1 or 2 battles.  If they are stupid and have no organization I try and inform them. If they will not listen, I do not preach, I leave.  There is no honor in dying from the stupids.  I have been with some great groups and I make a point to tell the puller and tanks and blasters what a great job they are doing and thank them for getting Mob&#8217;s off me.  I have also had groups give me special loot in payment for a job well done as healer or buffer (hint for you warrior types).  We have chosen a path that does not have much glory in the battle as far as melee goes. We wont see a crit hit for 187 damage but it is a reward to see our tanks health go up ½ bubble and he prevails over the AoF and we win the day for all the group.<br>	I may have said some things that you do not agree with and that is ok. I do not claim to be all knowing. I am merely sharing what I have come to know as a good plan.  <br><br><br>Curr the Shaman of Akh Velahr, 42 rite of Passage, of Terris Thule<br><br>&#8220; You can be old and still be immature&#8230;&#8230;&#8221;<br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
